# {{ .name }}

An Intropy **extractor block**: a console job that reads records from the `{{ .sourceSystem }}`
external system through the `{{ .connector }}` connector and publishes each raw record onto the
`{{ .publishesTopic }}` topic. How the source is reached (the transport) is chosen later, at
`intropy system create`.

This scaffold is **complete and runnable on its own** — no other components and no shared
infrastructure required.

## Run it standalone

```bash
task run          # seed the inbound folder, then dapr run one extraction pass and exit
```

`task run` seeds `./local/storage/inbound` with `local/sample-data/sample-source.json`, then runs the
job once. It is a console one-shot job (no web endpoints): the runner lists the source connector,
publishes each record onto the topic, deletes the consumed file, and exits — `dapr run` follows it
down. The connector defaults to a **local file binding** (`bindings.localstorage`) reading that
folder, and pub/sub is **in-memory** — both live in `local/dapr-components/`. Watch the logs to see
each record published (there is no subscriber standalone; that is the job of downstream components in
a system).

## Run it as part of a system

The same component runs unchanged inside a system; the SystemHost swaps the Dapr components folder at
run time so `binding.{{ .connector }}` becomes the connector's real transport and `pubsub` becomes
Redis. Scaffold the other components next to this folder, then from the parent directory:

```bash
intropy system create -n <system-name>
dotnet run --project <SystemName>.SystemHost -- check   # validate the topology
dotnet run --project <SystemName>.SystemHost            # run the whole system locally
```

This component's edge intent (block kind, connector, published topic) is recorded in
`.intropy/scaffold.json`, which `intropy system create` reads to wire the SystemHost.
